main event: The document describes an incident that occurred on 20 July 1948 near The Hague, Holland, where a cylindrical object resembling a V-2 rocket was observed by the chief of the KLM fleet and his daughter.
interesting points: The report is skeptical of the observers' claim of seeing an aircraft with two decks and no wings traveling at supersonic speeds, suggesting it could be a subjective impression or an ordinary aircraft or fireball.
The document humorously suggests a link between this incident and the famous 'Chiles-Whitted ship' sighting which occurred just four days later.

Dr. Hynek's evaluations from the Project Grudge report are referenced, outlining incidents with high, fair, or low probability of being astronomical in nature along with those lacking evident explanations.
The report mentions 34 incidents that remain unexplained, suggesting that errors in identification and hasty conclusions contribute to unexplainable reports.
Some numbers and passages appear to be partially redacted or unclear, indicating potential attempts to conceal certain details of the incident.
